<dl id="n36147h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36147h">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36147h"> 147(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> mental companionship / with mates <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n36147h"><li>FW 545.07 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/lexrB.htm#n36147h">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/l39rB.htm#n36147h">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n36147h">MS BL 47484b-460</ms> </li><li>JJA 59:207 <a name="rBd14y" href="../../ff/fdra/rda.htm#rBd14y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rB/rBd14.htm#n36147h">Draft: III&sect;3B.14</a>+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The husband commonly finds his chief interests <mark>among his &ldquo;mates&rdquo;</mark> and seldom rises even to the idea of <mark>mental companionship</mark> with his wife. He rarely ill-treats her; but restricted education and a narrow circle of activities hinder comradeship, and lack of mental touch tends to pass into unconscious neglect or active selfishness. <small> B. Seebohm Rowntree, <a name="BSRP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BSRP"><cite title="source">Poverty, A Study of Town Life</cite></a>, 3rd ed.? (1922) 109</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
